    deepDive: 'Serverless trades control for convenience, and the tradeoffs are specific. Cold starts: when a function scales up a new execution environment, the first request pays an initialization latency (tens of milliseconds to seconds depending on runtime and package size) — fine for async work, sometimes painful for user-facing APIs, mitigated with provisioned concurrency. Statelessness is mandatory: functions keep nothing between invocations, so all state lives in a database or object store. Execution limits (max duration, memory) make serverless a poor fit for long-running or heavy batch jobs. The pricing model inverts the usual calculus — serverless is dramatically cheaper for spiky, low-average traffic (you pay nothing at idle) but can be more expensive than reserved instances at sustained high volume. Container-based serverless (Fargate, Cloud Run) splits the difference: standard container images, no servers to manage, fewer runtime constraints than pure functions.',
